Mitch,

You&#39;ve noticed quite a discussion by proxy.  I&#39;m interested in _your_ 
position.  Without knowing more about your domain, I can guess that 
depency injection might be a better option than making the method 
protected, but probably for reasons other than simplicity of the 
resulting code or interface.  What are these reasons in your situtation?

     David Saff

Mitch Christensen wrote:

&gt; In my case, I know exactly what the problem is.  The private method 
&gt; relies on external resources that are not available during unit 
&gt; testing (i.e. Torque/DBMS).
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; My question was not how to find an unknown failure, but how to 
&gt; eliminate a known failure caused by an external dependency buried 
&gt; inside a private method.
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; For public/protected method dependencies, I extend the class under 
&gt; test and override and simplify those methods.  Unfortunately, this 
&gt; doesnâ€™t work for private methods.
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; I think the answer is to refactor the private method to support some 
&gt; form of dependency injection so I can insert mock objects that 
&gt; eliminate the exception.
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; My question was whether they may be a better/more efficient approach?
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; Thanks again for your help.
&gt;
&gt; -Mitch
