&gt; J. B. Rainsberger wrote:
&gt;
&gt; &gt; If you have a failing test, but you aren&#39;t sure why it fails, and you
&gt; &gt; suspect the problem is in a private method, what do you generally do?
&gt;
&gt; If I have a failing test that fails because an exception is thrown out
&gt; of a private method, I debug it. First off I eyeball the code both in
&gt; the private method and the public method being tested. Most of the time
&gt; the reason for the failure is obvious. If it&#39;s not, I&#39;ll generally set a
&gt; breakpoint or two and step through the code in the debugger and watch
&gt; what actually happens. This is a lot more productive than guessing at
&gt; what the problem might be. If I could guess right, then I wouldn&#39;t need
&gt; to step through it.
&gt;
&gt; It used to be common in quality code to do a code review by stepping
&gt; through the entire program in a debugger. This tended to reveal a lot of
&gt; surprises about how the code was really working. This technique has
&gt; fallen out of favor as applications grew larger. It&#39;s really impractical
&gt; today. However, when something is going wrong in a known piece of code
&gt; nothing beats single stepping through it in a debugger. This almost
&gt; always points me to the exact statement where what I think the code is
&gt; doing diverges from what the code is actually doing.
&gt;
&gt; This requires that the bug is consistently reproducible and I have a
&gt; test that reproduces it. However, once I&#39;ve got that I&#39;m good to go.
&gt; Writing hypothetical tests for what I think the bug might be only works
&gt; if the bug is so obvious that I can eyeball it in the first place. The
&gt; tricky bugs are the ones where everything looks like it should work and
&gt; I can&#39;t see why it doesn&#39;t. That&#39;s when I need to isolate the problem
&gt; more closely than a test method can. I need to find out which statement
&gt; is failing, not which method is failing. I already know the answer to
&gt; the latter question.
&gt;
&gt; If the bug proves to be deep inside another piece of code, then I might
&gt; later add a second test that aims more closely at the bug. However,
&gt; that&#39;s only done after I&#39;ve identified the bug, and often I don&#39;t even
&gt; bother to do that. After all, there&#39;s already at least one test for the
&gt; issue.
